C# 14 enhances its elegant null-safety tools by allowing null-conditional operators ?. and ?[] to appear on the left-hand side of assignment expressions. This new capability removes repetitive null checks and brings a new level of composability and safety to common mutation patterns in object graphs and collections. In this post, you’ll explore: What is null-conditional assignment What's new in C# 14 Real-world usage examples Supported assignment operations Limitations and best practices Before C# 14, you needed explicit null checks before assigning to a property: if (customer is not null) { customer.Order = GetCurrentOrder(); }
Or use a ternary: customer?.Order = customer is not null ? GetCurrentOrder() : null;
