C# 14 brings a new level of flexibility and readability to lambda expressions by allowing parameter modifiers like ref, out, in, and scoped in untyped parameter lists. Previously, to use any modifier, you had to explicitly declare the parameter types. Now, the compiler infers the types while still allowing these powerful modifiers — reducing verbosity in functional programming constructs and delegate definitions. In this post, you’ll learn: What modifiers can be used with lambda parameters What changed in C# 14 Examples with ref, out, and scoped
